Rafael Correa à Quito, us Mondays.
To found the republic on a socialism of its own in the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chavez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
On Sunday, following the example of colleagues and friends, it was the latter who gave voice to the project of a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since, according to official results, 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, on a vote basis of 80%.
According to these results, the "no" was 28%, while 7% of the vote was null and 0.7% white ballots.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it should get half of the votes, plus one.
On Sunday, two polls carried out at the exit of polling stations and an estimate of a non-governmental organization had announced an overwhelming "yes" victory, placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had, on the other hand, claimed the victory of his draft Constitution on the night between Sunday and Monday.
The "Constitution has triumphed gloriously", he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians within the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As always, Chavez and Morales congratulated Rafael Correa, as did his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The ballot, which took place calmly according to the election observation mission of the Organization of American States (OEA), was based on a 444-point text designed to consolidate the "new socialism" defended by the president.
This draft Constitution consecrates the power of the state over the economy, reserving it the "planning of development" of a country that essentially lives off the oil extraction carried out by large foreign companies and consequently their currency.
Conceived by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants more power to the head of state, who can be elected for two consecutive terms of four years, to have the opportunity to dissolve the assembly.
Correa has already announced its intention to take advantage of this amendment and to re-apply for a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also states the gratuity of health and education services, which the president has begun to promote in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also prohibits the presence of foreign troops, a provision that will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts seized ten days ago.
I'm in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian chaperones held captive in the desert for ten days were safely returned to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
By the morning, they had been liberated in Chad by an Egyptian commando.
Apparently in good shape, the hostages arrived at Almaza military base, near Cairo International Airport, around 3:30 p.m., on board a special plane.
On board a helicopter, they were transferred immediately, without being able to give any interviews to the press, to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for analysis.
They enjoy "good health" and have not been paid any ransom "to the kidnappers," Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the airstrip.
Kidnapped on 19 September during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, bordering Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been tossed from hideout to hideout by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The group consisted of 11 tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – and 8 Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of Aegyptous, the safari organizing agency.
An Egyptian security official said that 30 members of the special forces, aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night, just before dawn.
"There were gunfire, half of the kidnappers were killed, while the others fled," said the perpetrator who requested to maintain anonymity.
He explained that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "blink" unit were sent to Sudan, where they would be supported by German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini stressed, from Belgrade, the importance of the role of Italian secret agents and special forces.
We have to admit that if we achieved such a result it was thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of the men of our secret services, of the special forces," he said, without adding any further details.
He also denied payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army of patrol claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle in which the kidnappers were on board and to have killed six, including the Chadian leader of the kidnappers, and to have captured two.
According to the army, the kidnappers are linked to a Darfur rebel organization, the Sudan Liberation Movement (SLA_U), a claim immediately denied by the latter.
Letters- The Silent Majority of Culture
On the front page is a debate on the funding of the culture on which the current election campaign focuses.
All the better.
But a part of our cultural life always remains in the shadows.
Who will pronounce himself to denounce the meager sums granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical places that are starving?
What politician will dare to remind the federal government that it is neglecting monuments and heritage buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we don't have any real laws that actually preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government is paying three and a half million euros for the restoration of Chinon Castle in the Loire Valley alone?
Among our American neighbors, it is the Constitution that affirms that the protection of heritage is part of national culture and that the same heritage must be protected by every citizen, every political authority and every government department, and all this by mutual agreement.
In Québec, at the Federation of Historic Societies of Québec, there are at least 40 000 volunteers who, grouped into 211 societies for the preservation of historical, genealogical, archives and heritage preserve, with little money, private archives and archaeological sites.
It is they who, often, defend our heritage, who protest with the energy of despair when real estate entrepreneurs and decision-makers attack our forgotten remains and cemeteries with their bulldozers.
When will the right space be reserved for history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states help through partial nationalisation the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which ended up in difficulty first in Europe for the crisis of the American credit market: the three nations will provide 11.2 billion euros to the financial institution - insurance with interest also in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands agreed on the weekend at the highest level, also involving the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
In the euro area the first major crisis in the context of the difficulties in which the international financial market has been struggling for more than a year is that of the Fortis bank, and from a certain point of view the decisions taken in this regard can set a precedent.
Under the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states will hold nearly half (49%) of the bank's share in the country.
The bank will almost certainly sell part of its interests, including first of all the assets, especially insurance, of the Dutch ABN Amro acquired a year ago.
Last week Fortis's shares had started with a vertical collapse, serious signs of the institute's crisis then showed up in the second half of the week.
Analysts, however, agree that the bank, with 85,000 employees, is too large to allow it to go bankrupt.
The bank's shares fell nearly 12% on Friday, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of the shares has decreased by more than two-thirds.
Considering current share prices the group's entire capital value is around €14 billion, but according to the bank's executives this value is not real.
The corporate summit blames the collapse of Fortis shares on the uncertainties of the non-European market due to the acceptance of the US $700 billion plan.
On Monday, the title slowly started to rise again.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank's new CEO.
The financial institution has also sought private buyers but so far no one has come forward with a worthy offer.
The Belgian government had previously assured that investors should not fear losing money.
There was no panic among the bank's customers, the branches were not assaulted.
In Hungary Fortis owns autonomous subsidiaries and has also purchased leasing companies.
The fox in the henhouse
In America, life and health insurers, based on people's medical purchase data, often refuse to enter into an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a privacy program according to which the use of prescription drug data depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like entrusting the henhouse to the fox" - writes the Washington Post quoting Richard Dick author of the program to follow the prescriptions of medicines.
Insurance companies make the insurance rate and the amount due in the event of claims subject to the health status of any customer and if they consider the risk too high they do not take out the insurance.
A while ago the client had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was concluded only after the outcome of the examination.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: based on the customer's identification code you can easily get information from pharmacies about which medicines he has purchased in the last year and a half and from this the program shows what diseases he suffers and in what health conditions he is in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers this means that your blood fat level is incurably high and is classified in the highest risk category.
On the market there are various versions of the program, some also determine the risk multiplier, to the insurer so in addition to paper work there is not much left, even if there are small difficulties.
Among the cons is that some medicines are usable for multiple purposes, e.g. some compounds are employable against migraines or hot flushes, but are also effective against depression.
The latter, from an insurance - commercial point of view, applies as a risk increase factor, the first two do not.
For the request and processing of data, separate companies have been formed and these, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the approval of the patient.
Now the authorities force them to do so even though they have not so far imposed fines for negligence.
Some companies lately also process the result of laboratory tests and link them to the medicine consumption data in order to provide a more precise picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to the data and at the same time the control of the use will be more and more difficult.
There is a separate privacy law but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of Congress there is a bill that gives the authorities control competence to companies specialized in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: that is why he has developed a program that links data forwarding with the approval expressed by the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot so much deny approval because otherwise insurers do not enter into the contract.
So then eventually the hens are entrusted to the leniency of the fox.
