European Union and India double trade
Since the European Union and India are partners who trade mainly with each other, the agenda of the ninth summit meeting was also dominated by this issue, as well as all other global problems.
Today there will be a Franco-Indian summit that will deal primarily with cooperation on atomic energy.
The European Union recognises that India is becoming a major democratic power that should be given more voice in international affairs, but member countries have not yet been able to decide whether or not to support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
So there was no insistence on this issue at the ninth summit held yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as President-in-Office of the Union, José Manuel Barroso Chairman of the Commission and Javier Solana High Representative for Foreign Affairs received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they found the agreement to double in 5 years, i.e. increase to 100 billion euros, trade.
Considering that between 2000 and 2007 the exchange of goods rose from 25 to 55 billion, this is not too ambitious a goal.
As a result, the 26 bilateral civil flight agreements have been legally unified, so air traffic can also start in the future.
India would like to sign the free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the deal.
The goal is to balance because while the EU is India's first trading partner, New Delhi instead is only in ninth place among the EU's partners.
The summit paid attention to global affairs.
To the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan and to terrorism, the latter condemned in all its forms on both sides, and urged the convening of a UN conference.
They urged the conclusion of the Doha Trade Round, although both sides played a role in the failure of this.
