Steve Fossett's plane found, billionaire missing a year ago
The wreckage of Steve Fossett's plane was found, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying in the Nevada desert.
The wreckage was found on a plateau at an altitude of 3,000 meters, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammoth Lakes, on the border of California and Nevada.
Inside the aircraft, however, there were no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson dispelled the doubts that still remained: "The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that it's just the one Steve Fossett was flying on the day he disappeared," he said at a news conference.
The sheriff then specified that no human remains were found either in the plane, or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was pronounced dead in February.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Bureau (NTSB) said a few hours after the wreck was sighted, a team of investigators was dispatched, who then identified the device: it is the Bellanca 8kcab, missing since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, also in California, not far from the Nevada border, some personal belongings of Fossett had been found by a couple near their Mammoth Lakes home.
These are two documents with Fossett's name, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a hoodie.
Fossett's research had been interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had won a place in history thanks to a long series of primates.
By 2002, on the sixth attempt, he had become the first man to complete the world tour in an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flying.
Three years later he had toured the world by plane and nonstop.
Among his many records, also that of flying at 15,445 meters high, over the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
